choices.text:
a sin and a personal sin. I think we have to have measures in place that everybody knows that abortion is not the first option. UNICEF administers vaccinations and monitors the health of Afghan children. However, with limited funding and support for the Afghan Ministry of Health, corners are being cut.

There's been no information coming to the mothers of the fact that there are these alternatives. They're not knowledgeable. They don't understand. They're very young to begin with, and they're not getting the right level of education and information to make those choices themselves.

Some doctors have sought my help because they fear they will be fired for speaking out about the increase in illegal abortions in Afghanistan. Some of the organizations doing the reviews also disallow doctors from campaigning against unsafe abortions.

The name of the game always is that the allies believe that the Afghans must never be informed of this information and must never be allowed to make decisions for themselves. Trusting foreign aid agencies perhaps smacks of colonialism. Vilifying them or their employees smacks of anti-farsi. Is the answer that we stop spending money in a country that still doesn't have a bank, more hospitals or any form of medicine? Afghanistan imports 40 tons of food, yet it squanders its resources. Since 1978, Afghanistan experienced four wars and an orgy of internal killings. A world without electricity and one quarter of the population engaged in the opium industry. Agriculture is corrupt, technology has never been a priority
